\title{\textbf{HLRT Geo-EM Amplifier}\\
\large Experimental Device for Electromagnetic-Lattice Coupling\\
\normalsize GitHub Repository Documentation}

\author{Ryan Tabor}

\date{August 18, 2025}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The HLRT Geo-EM Amplifier is an experimental device designed to demonstrate electromagnetic current amplification through spacetime lattice coupling effects. The device predicts a reproducible 5-6\% current boost when electromagnetic fields interact with the underlying hexagonal lattice structure at $\lambda \approx 1.24 \times 10^{-13}$ m. This repository contains the complete hardware specifications, controller code, and simulation framework for peer review and replication.
\end{abstract}

\section{Device Overview}

The Geo-EM Amplifier is a 32×32×5 cm modular tile containing:

\begin{itemize}
\item Central electromagnetic coil (120 turns, 26 AWG, 5 cm diameter)
\item Energy storage system (4× BCAP3000 supercapacitors)
\item Pi Pico 2W controller with safety systems
\item Conductive graphene-enhanced PETG hull
\item Professional measurement instrumentation
\end{itemize}

\section{Predicted Effect}

The amplifier targets electromagnetic current amplification according to:

\begin{equation}
I_{\text{enhanced}} = I_{\text{baseline}} \times \left(1 + 0.05 + 0.01 \times \min\left(1, \left(\frac{V}{10}\right)^2\right)\right)
\end{equation}

Expected results:
\begin{itemize}
\item Baseline current: 10.0 A
\item Enhanced current: 10.6 A 
\item Current boost: 5-6\%
\item Test duration: 5 seconds
\item PWM frequency: 1 kHz at 60\% duty cycle
\end{itemize}

