\section{Replication Guidelines}

\subsection{Prerequisites}
\begin{itemize}
\item 3D printer capable of PETG+CF (350×320×325mm minimum)
\item Standard electronics workbench with soldering equipment
\item Professional measurement instruments (oscilloscope, current probe)
\item Python 3.12+ with numpy, scipy, matplotlib, sympy
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Build Timeline}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Day 1}: 3D print hull (8 hours), wind coil, program controllers
\item \textbf{Day 2}: Assembly, surface treatment, component integration
\item \textbf{Day 3}: System testing, validation runs, data collection
\end{itemize}

\section{Expected Results}

Upon successful replication, experimenters should observe:

\begin{itemize}
\item Consistent 5-6\% current amplification during PWM activation
\item Reproducible results across multiple test runs (<5\% variance)
\item Correlation between simulation predictions and measured values
\item Spatial effects detectable with precision laser measurement
\end{itemize}

\section{Peer Review Invitation}

This repository provides complete specifications for independent verification of electromagnetic-lattice coupling effects. All hardware components are commercially available, software is open-source, and methodologies are fully documented.

We invite the scientific community to:
\begin{itemize}
\item Review the theoretical framework and simulation code
\item Replicate the experimental apparatus
\item Validate the predicted 5-6\% current amplification
\item Contribute improvements and variations
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Contact}: Available through GitHub issues and discussions.

